Reasoning: The paper discusses the social structure of gender in online and offline friendship networks, which falls under the scope of social networks and computational social science (cs.SOC). The paper also uses machine learning methods to predict gender based on network structure, which falls under the scope of machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses privacy concerns related to attribute prediction, which falls under the scope of cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) and computer security and privacy (cs.CR). Finally, the paper uses statistical methods to analyze the structure of homophily and monophily in social networks, which falls under the scope of statistics (cs.ST) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
